t experiences, infusing the discussion of laws and standards with intimate examples and sophisticated analyses. Looking to the future, she ponders how international institutions such as the ILO will address labor market informality alongside national and regional law reform. Regardless of what comes next, Everyday Transgressions establishes that domestic workers' victory is a victory for the ILO and for all those who struggle for an inclusive, transnational vision of labor law, rooted in social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aForeign workersxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aHousehold employeesxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aLabor laws and legislation, International. 4aLabor History. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aSociology & Social Science.  aDecent Work for Domestic Workers Convention No. 189.  aDecent Work for Domestic Workers.  aHousehold employees legal status.  aInternational Labour Organization convention.  aInternational Labour Organization history .  aInternational Labour Organization.  aLabor & Employment.  aLabor & Industrial Relations.  aLabor laws and legislation.  aNational Domestic Workers Alliance.  aStudies in Working-Class History.  aactivists.  adomestic worker labor law.  adomestic worker rights.  adomestic workers protection.  adomestic workers' human rights.  adomestic workers' legal rights.  adomestic workers' rights.  adomestic workers'.  adomestic workers.  aemployment law.  ahousehold employees .  ainfluence of the domestic workers.  alabor activists.  alabor and politics.  alabor law historians .  alabor law.  alabor policy historians.  alabor relations .  alabor studies .  alegal historian .  alegal history.  alegal studies .  apolicy historians.  asocial justice .  asocial stratification.  atransnational legal 